We have enjoyed this chant with a drone as well as a capella. One of the interesting aspects of the movement is that the downbeat falls on the second time the word One is said, but the mudrā happens on the first ``One'', so the movements occur in between downbeats, or on the odd measures, creating two interlocking cycles.
\subsection{Hrīṃ Shrīṃ Klīṃ Param Īśvari Swaha}


The following chant --- at least in majickal terms --- is an incantation to cultivate the 
\emph{divine feminine}. The first three terms are considered \emph{seed syllables}  or \emph{bījākṣara} (\saha{बीजाक्षर}) often simply referred to just by the term \emph{bīja	 } (pronounced \emph{bee --- ya}) (\saha{बीज}) (Jp. 種子 shuji) (Chinese 种子 zhǒng zǐ), meaning \emph{seed}. The \textbf{bīja} --- a term common to both Hinduism and Buddhism --- don't have a specific literal meaning, but are known to vibrate sympathetically with certain universal principals, or what Jung might have called \emph{archetypes}. Om (\saha{ॐ}) is the most well-known and 
possibly most fundamental bīja, signifying the sound of the universe beginning and also the frequency at which it continues to vibrate (432 Hz or around a C$\sharp$). In all three of the syllables, the vowel sound is ``eee'', like in ``cream''. \textbf{Hrīṁ} (\saha{ह्रीं}) engages the \textbf{para śakti} and \textbf{hrit padma}. \par
